				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What do you think you're doing while twisting, RP wise?<a name="54999"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 3 04 7:00 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>In my opinion Duvenu is right on the money with mentioning a fugue.  A Fugue has multiple melodic lines in a single piece.  They compliment and contrast against one another.
<br />

<br />
I would say with twisting.. and the various songs starting at different points, the closest musical equivilent is a &quot;Stretto Fugue&quot;.  Stretto is the italian word for bridge.  In a Stretto Fugue the melodic themes overlap, with one starting before the prior one (or ones) have ended (think row row row your boat, but more complex). The description of a Stretto Fugue perfectly describes twisting to me.
<br />

<br />
This is why my Molto Espressivo bard is named &quot;Stretto Fugue&quot;</span></td>
