			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What do you think you're doing while twisting, RP wise?<a name="55048"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 4 04 7:20 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The most common definition of bard songs is that the music of the bard is actually a form of magical spell. So the roleplaying aspect is that by beating on my drum or tambourine I am invoking similar magical energies to those an enchanter might for their DoTs, but just through a different medium. Much as a shaman invokes the same effect by invoking spirits as a necro does by magical study into the dead.
<br />

<br />
You should not necessarily look upon the music itself as causing the damage, so much as the magic the music brings about that does so. In this respect the comparison to real life is pointless since the very definition implies a magical world. Song duration is easy to explain by the magical energies resonating out and fading away after a few (15ish) seconds. In this explanation you are literally playing one song after another continuously. Or perhaps I should say one excerpt from a song that is truly a sung (or played) spell.
<br />

<br />
In other words, the roleplaying definition is precisely the same as the game mechanics. You start a spell every 3 seconds the spell effects last a short time. The only difference from real spells is that the songs do not require somatic components and hence can be cast on the move. Isn't a definition that matched the way the game works simple enough?
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
