			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What do you think you're doing while twisting, RP wise?<a name="55091"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 4 04 11:24 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>How can one have a post on twisting without mentioning the immortal Chubby Checkers  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" /> 
<br />

<br />
From a role playing perspective, and this goes for more than just twisting, I have always viewed a bard's song as his way of manipulating the nature of the world surrounding him.  When he is twisting, he is merely shifting the way he is altering the way he is changing the nature of the world to create multiple effects.
<br />

<br />
From a music standpoint, listening to a single theme is like listening to a 5 year old play simple songs on a piano, great if its your own kid, but painful otherwise.  There are not a great many diatonic composers that I care to listen to, Carl Orff is about it.  You don't even have to get too complex for music to be good, John Williams themes may not involve a great deal of texture, but woven together they make a great tapestry.  That is what a bard does when he twists <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
