			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What do you think you're doing while twisting, RP wise?<a name="55644"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 8 04 1:25 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Well, ever listen to Nine Inch Nails or AC/DC?  They layer music.  Starting with one element, repeating it for a while, then adding something else (starting with a bassline, adding drums, then guitar or synth, for example).  This is how I envision twisting.  Depending on the situation, I change the tune - so, I think of bards who use twisting programs as the equivelant to Elevator Musicians.  Being a musician myself in RL, I can't help but be something of a snob, and love the idea of music being powerful <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" /> . 
<br />
 From a roleplaying perspective, I don't try to think of it as being Scientifically justified.  I consider it as magically amplified musical effects.  For example, most people who listen to Samuel Barber's Adagio for Strings feel sad and enervated (Mesmerization or slow), whereas Van Halens &quot;Jump&quot; tends to excite people (haste, or selos).  On the X-Games (skateboarders, BMX Bikers and Rollerbladers) will have high speed punk music playing, to keep them alert and focused.  Tibetan monks keep continuous throat chants going (Kazumi's song of preservation), because they find it serene, and believe it brings them closer to god.  Most religions incorporate music into their rituals, because of it's effect on the psyche (Call of the Banshee? <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" /> ).  In a world of magic, the effect of these songs could be amplified in very strange ways, and used to incredible effect.
<br />
I love that sony included bard, and actually did a much better job with them than TCR and Wizards of the Coast with the D&amp;D version of bard.  The sense of timing and alertness necessary to play a bard well, is not entirely unlike that of a musician remaining focused on reading and/or performing music.  In essence, it can be an art.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.pravda-of-norrath.com/">Midwinter</a> 
